metadata.name: Rêve em Nuvens #6
metadata.description:
Even though sometimes our horizon seems to be obscured by problems and difficulties, the weather is always clear above the clouds.

"Rêves em Nuvens", a mixture of French and Portuguese words meaning "Dreams in the clouds", is intended to be a message of hope and encouragement for all those who, at some point, have seen their perspectives disappear. They are still there, the stars and the sky are only hidden behind clouds.

Born from a two-month collaboration between Omar Lobato and Estienne, "Rêve em Nuvens" uses noise assemblages to reproduce a cloudy sky, sometimes at night under a full moon, during a late afternoon or a sunny day. 

The colors, shape, texture and turbulence of the clouds are all variations that will give this series a style that can be both realistic and fantastic.

Although the parameters are attached to the hash of each edition, certain options are offered in order to be able to generate the image in the style that suits you best, whether for display on screen, or for printing:

Press the [1] key to toggle the noise effect
Press the [2] key to toggle the stucco texture
Press the [3] key to toggle the lines texture

Press the [S] key to save a 4K image in PNG format

Add "?size=xxx" at the end of the url to generate an image of xxx pixels

Authors: Omar Lobato & Estienne
May 2022
NFT 2.0 license

metadata.name: M-tore #42
metadata.description: This token generates abstract art using a recursive algorithm for rectangle splitting. The number of rectangles can be anywhere from 32 to 16384. There are several different strategies for splitting, each one producing distinctive results. The background can be dark or light. Color palettes are generated programmatically in eight different ways (e.g. monochromatic, complementary, analogous, etc.). Textures and effects are also generated programmatically using Perlin noise and pixel manipulation. To add dynamics, there is a probability of having some uncertainty in drawing rectangles, dots, and lines.

metadata.name: Action Fields #31
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.

metadata.name: Shift #249
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles — dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ’s’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Drone Beast synthesizer #49
metadata.description:
This is a little Drone Beast with a modular synthesizer inside. Being made of thousands of particles swarming around several attractors it reacts on different signals across the modular patch. The patch itself is based on multiple 8-bit oscillators, modulating each other and being modulated by mathematical expressions, unique for each Beast.

Press anywhere in the frame to hear the sound. Use your mouse to explore the space of drone, which is individual for each Beast. Press "a" to toggle auto-evolution.

All remaining editions (if any) will be burnt in 2 days.

@ferluht, @alexexeev, 2022

metadata.name: Permutation City #43
metadata.description:
The work is inspired by the novel Permutation City by Greg Egan, the author of the hard science fiction.

It raises the issue of whether we can in principle understand that we exist in reality or in a simulation.

According to the Theory of Dust (which is described in the novel), the universe is simulatable and all other possible universes are equally as real as ours, emerging spontaneously from their own mathematical self-consistency. Human consciousness is Turing-computable, which means that consciousness can be also produced by a computer program.

The Autoverse is an artificial life simulator, a massive complex cellular automaton universe, producing cities and the consciousness of human copies.

Gradually, due to failures and a lack of computing power, the idea of the reliability of such universes is destroyed. 

Spaces crumble, cities become fluid and drain down, turning into dust and digital glitch.

Thanks to Yulikolay for helping with code, using p5.Riso.js library for generating files suitable for risograph printing.
Source images for permutation cities are made with a help of DALL·E mini neural network.

metadata.name: Bipole #2
metadata.description:
Two meandering paths are created with opposite flow vectors. The paths are drawn with a twisty drip brush.

Created for #tezos4tezos in May 2022.

Features 
- The amount each stroke's bristles twist as the path is drawn
- If each paths starts off strong or soft
- Splats at the starts and ends of the path
- Dark mode
- Monochrome or colored lines (colors from the p5riso palette)
- Paper fibers in the background
- 10% chance of dark orange and black lines

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2400px by 1483px

metadata.name: Seasons #217
metadata.description:
Seasons depicts monolithic mountains and calm seas scattered with unnatural elements.
The color palettes explore the colors of natural landscapes through different times of year.

To ease browser load, the images are paused by default.
Hitting 'p' will toggle a subtle animation.
Hitting 't' will toggle between the day and night palette for the image.
On mobile the resolution is reduced and the image is always paused to ease the load on the device.

Generative images by 0x3739
twitter.com/0x3739
library: twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library
license: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Tested and functioning correctly on Google Chrome version 100.0.4896.88 on Windows desktop and Android mobile device.

The work is rendered in webgl as a fragment shader.
Setting parameters in the javascript portion of the script generates a different fragment shader for each iteration.

Interactions
'-' to zoom in.
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'z' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to A4/A3/A2/A1 format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
'q' to change the aspect ratio to portrait.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
'p' to pause the animation the image.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the margins on the image.
'm' to toggle the mountains in the image.
'c' to toggle the clouds in the image.
'g' to toggle the grid in the image.
'd' to toggle the dirt speckles in the image.
'n' to toggle the noise in the image.
'j' to toggle the jitter in the image.
'v' to toggle all vintage effects in the image.
'1' to toggle the stars in the image.
'2' to toggle the moons in the image.
'3' to toggle the black squares in the image.
'4' to toggle the white squares in the image.
'5' to toggle the primary color squares in the image.
'6' to toggle the secundary color squares in the image.
'7' to toggle the colour correction in the image.
'8' to toggle the sea in the image.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash. 
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.
